WE ARE THRILLED TO FINALLY RELEASE OUR ICEBREAKER COLLECTION! 🩵💜 We have been working with the brilliant @hannahgraceauthor for a few months now perfecting this exclusive collection for you. We wanted it to truly represent all the magic of Icebreaker and capture what Stassie & Nate might wear at UCMH, as well as your favourite quotes from the book. We hope you love it as much as we do! Hannah has been amazing and deserves every success that follows with the Icebreaker series, it’s an incredible book and we loved it. We can’t wait for Wildfire to be released in October. To make things even more special, Hannah has chosen a wonderful LGBT+ organisation @the_proud_trust 🌈where 10% of all proceeds from the sweatshirts will be donated to. We are bursting with pride (literally!!!!! happy pride month!) and feel so lucky that we have been able to collaborate with someone so wonderful, as well as The Pride Trust. A bit about them: 

The Proud Trust is a life changing charity providing support and education to ensure that all young people know that being LGBT+ is something to be proud of. 

The Proud Trust delivers youth work and one-to-one support across Greater Manchester and Cheshire. The charity also runs a national training and inclusion programme for schools, Proud Connections Live Chat, and manages Manchester’s LGBT+ Centre, The Proud Place.! #Icebreaker

yesterday i asked you to tell me about your goal for the rest of 2023 and today i'm going to share mine: 

✨ MISSION: The #23for23 initiative amplifies and elevates marginalized voices in publishing by promoting, showcasing, and celebrating the works of Black, Indigenous, and People of Color dedicated to telling stories that center marginalized identities. ✨

you might have seen this graphic floating around instagram since steamy lit con last weekend and i'm here to encourage you to get involved like i am. 

the challenge itself is super easy because you have so much choice. all you need to do is read 23 books centring marginalised identities by bipoc authors by the end of 2023. then review, shout about, and create content to shine a spotlight on these stories and authors.

small changes to your buying habits help lead to the big changes we can all agree are desperately needed in an industry where marginalised identities are shamefully underrepresented.

it is not enough to say 'i want to read diversely' and hope it magically happens. we all need to commit to being mindful and intentional with our book buying. so many incredible stories are flying under the radar and we're all missing out. 

this graphic is available on 23for23.net which also has a list of books to read if you're not sure where to start.

i have my first read selected which i'll be starting next week once i've submitted my draft but i'd love to hear your suggestions for my other reads and if you're going to take part too. 

for recommendations 📚💘: i like adult romance but don't mind if it's open or closed door. i prefer older characters but i do read college. marriage of convenience is my favourite trope. ironically, i'd rather not read hockey right now (i don't read it when i'm working on my own book). i don't read books with infertility plots. i love longer books!

EXCITING NEWS: Wildfire is getting an exclusive book club on @fable with @atriabooks, moderated by TikTok’s @thebookthief28! #WildfireOnFable

wildfire is a @libraryreads top pick 🥹🥹

i'm always incredibly honoured to get any form of nice feedback about my work but this one is particularly lovely. i spent so much of my childhood in the library — it was next to our supermarket so my mum would leave me there for while she did the big shop lol — so to be noticed by librarians feels extra special. 

✨ "This fun summer camp sports romance is a perfect beach read. The characters are complex, and the men (other than the ‘bad guys’) are written to be very respectful of and thoughtful to the women in their lives, whether in friendship or romance. The book is also very sex-positive. Readers who missed the first book in this series won’t feel like they are missing anything, but will want to catch up!" — Jennifer Lizak, Chicago Public Library, IL ✨

thank you so much to everyone involved 🏕️🐶🕊️🌸❤️‍🔥

hi besties. exciting uk special edition news! 🏕️🐶🕊️🧡💫 @theworksstores will be selling these beautiful sprayed edge copies of #wildfire from publication day — their first ever sprayed edge paperback exclusive! i’m so honoured because like any self respecting brit, i bloody love the works. this edition isn’t available to pre-order and will go on sale on the 3rd like the normal edition. when i was signing at the printers two weeks ago i got to see how they’re sprayed which is the coolest. run to your closest the works on pub day because they’re while stocks last. 🫶🏻🥰✨

i’m very lucky (and grateful) to say wildfire was included in b&n’s ‘best books of 2023’ in their romance category! i put a lot of myself into this book, which made it 10 times scarier to release, so to see it recognised and shouted about is really lovely.

in less positive news, and as excited as i am, i can’t help but feel disappointed at the lack of BIPOC authors included. this post is in no way suggesting that the other authors included on the list don’t deserve to be highlighted as well. i just see the wider conversation about lack of diversity on editorial lists and yet very little seems to change. 

this is an industry issue and not specifically a b&n issue. again, i am so lucky to receive the enthusiasm i do and the b&n staff i’ve met are wonderful. but the ‘well they’re nice and supportive of me’ energy isn’t it. i think it’s important to speak up about my discomfort as someone with a platform and a whole load of privilege to go with it. it’s possible to be happy for yourself/me and disheartened for others. 

readers hold so much power when it comes to what gets pushed. so even if you can't afford to buy every book you want to, which is totally understandable in this economy, support authors by marking as 'want to read', request at your local library, review the books you do read, and shout at publishers about what you want them to buy!

reading has taken a backseat for me this year due to my own writing commitments, health and travel, but you know what i’m really good at? buying books. 

swipe to have a sneaky peek at what’s on my kindle. i vowed to be more intentional with my reading choices last month for the #23for23 initiative and i’ve screenshotted my romance by BIPOC author folder. i’ve read several of these already (and they were wonderful) and i’ll be posting my reviews when i’m off deadline. i marked everything as unread to get rid of the little tab and make it look neat but forgot to do my current read lol. cheating with your marriage counsellor anyone?

to summarise, proud of my little daddy issues book but hoping to see more marginalised voices being celebrated soon.

let me know if you're read anything on my list. 💘

i'm truly terrible at writing these captions, but just know, i am beyond grateful.

better late than never, right?

starting off a post with “hi i’ve been number one on the new york times bestsellers list for three weeks” is not something i ever thought i’d have to do. it’s humbling and wonderful but terrifying and hard to process. 

every time i think “okay, this is it. things are about to be normal” you guys go lol no, and buy enough books and create enough excitement to cause something like this. 

i’m honoured that you, the readers and booksellers and librarians, continue to pick me. i do not take it for granted. thank you so so much. 

nothing would be possible without @kaitlinjolson who takes my inability to work to a deadline or commit to a geographical location in her stride. and @ifeanyoku who is graceful and understanding when i’m definitely pestering her. @meganrudloff @nycbookgirl @zakiyanjamal for working their hardest to make me look cool and relevant, and for putting the same amount of enthusiasm into cheering me on regardless of which week we’re on. 

thank you to the incredible untagged people at @atria who make things like this possible. i was very lucky to meet so many people last month and it really does take a village. thank you for making my release so special.

and finally, of course, @kimberlybrower2 who deserves to be credited in every post, because she’s the absolute best. 

— H xo
Did their one night together start a fire they can’t put out? Grab your copy of the # 1 NYT bestseller to find out 🔥

introducing daydream. 
book 3 in the maple hills series. 

i've never been asked for anything in my life more than i’ve been asked for this book. not even specifically THIS story, just more henry. i'm pretty sure i could have sent him on a quest through the peaceful streets of maple hills for 400 pages and you'd all be like cool, lemme get comfy with my kindle. 

i've never wanted to get something right as much as i do with this book. i feel like halle (yes, she's called halle. i can finally tell you!) and henry represent a lot of people in their early 20s. while it still has the same lighthearted vibe of my other books, it also tackles things like making friends as an adult and doing things because other people want you to (cough. becoming hockey captain). i've had so many ideas for what i wanted henry's book to look like, who i wanted him to be with, how his relationship would enhance how wonderful he already is. i'm really happy i landed here. 

as of right now, this book doesn't have a release date other than 'some time in summer 2024'. i know everywhere says 4th june, but that's just a holding date. when i have i 100%-not-going-to-change release date i'll post about it.

pre-order campaign won't be announced until next year so keep hold of your receipt and you'll still be eligible. 

special editions might be announced at a later date — i get asked to do them by the retailer, not the other way around so that's why i can't announce everything in one go like i'd like to. 

same with signed copies, i'll post if i get asked to do them. 

thank you to the wonderful @lenikauffman for another beautiful cover. this one is truly my favourite.

pre-order is live worldwide and please remember to support indie bookstores with your pre-orders!

out of all the things i might need to announce 42 weeks after release... being #1 on the new york times list was not on my bingo card. i think icebreaker has been in every spot 2-15 since it came out but she's never been in spot number 1. 🥹🥹

this caption may or may not make sense given the fact i'm very shocked and jetlagged right now! so as always, pretend you don't see if it's nonsense... 

i'm the luckiest woman in the world and i don't take any of this for granted. i promise i know i have the best readers out there.

what a way to finish the year. woke up to the loveliest email letting me know icebreaker hit 1 million sold across paperback, audiobook, and ebook in north america! it’s been a big month for milestones because it also reached 200k paperbacks in the uk and 100k paperbacks in australia which takes me to 1 million paperbacks sold worldwide since feb. this is more than i could have ever hoped for over my entire career. thank you for making my first year muddling through trying to do this author thing so special. congrats to my @simonandschuster family and thank you for your continued hard work. 🥹🥰🫶🏻

decided to get reflective and be a little bit vulnerable on the internet to kick off the new year. 🥂✨ 
given that nobody asked me for this, i hope you don't mind that i wanted to do something a little different by talking about the things that made my life better, and what you'll hear me saying a lot in 2024. 2023, you will always be famous to me. 🌝
please feel free to comment your 2024 goals or something that made your life better this year so i feel less like i just voluntarily posted my therapy notes on the internet xx
